<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aid Flights to Sarajevo To Resume 11 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001210894 Paris AFP in English 2057 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001210894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, Jan 10 (AFP) -- Relief flights into 
Sarajevo, suspended last week after an attack on the city's 
airport, are to resume Tuesday, UN High Commissioner for 
Refugees [UNHCR] spokesman Ron Redmond said Monday. 
  Redmond said UN officials had received new assurances from 
Bosnian Serbs and the Moslem-led Bosnian Government about the 
safety of aid flights, suspended after a rocket landed on the 
runway on January 5. The countries participating in the 
operation -- Germany, Canada, the United States, France, Britain 
and Norway -- had agreed to the resumption of flights, he added. 
  Redmond said 21 flights into the Bosnian capital were 
planned 
for Tuesday. The first aircraft of the day would be a Canadian 
plane flying out of Ancona in Italy. 
  An attempt was made on Sunday to resume the aid operation, 
but stopped after four flights because of the security situation 
around the capital. 

</TEXT>

