<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials React to `Partnership for Peace' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Roman: `Partnership' Disappointing </H4>
<F P=102> AU1101130694 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1100 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1101130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In connection with the NATO summit session held in 
Brussels, Mr. Petre Roman, president of the Democratic Party, 
president of the Commission for Defense, Public Order, and 
National Security in the Chamber of Deputies, and special 
rapporteur of the NATO Assembly for the new European security 
order, made a statement to our radio network in which he 
mentioned that the proceedings have concluded without any 
surprise. 
  The U.S. plan of partnership for peace was adopted. For the 
countries that belonged to the former Warsaw Pact, among them 
Romania, this can be considered as a disappointing result. 
Romania can consider itself a country that deserves to have a 
more reassuring status for its own national security. 
  Mr. Roman also said that the plan for partnership for peace 
represents a compromise between the direct request of the former 
socialist countries to be accepted in NATO and Russia's 
insistent demand not to have such an expansion of that 
organization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

