<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Requests Coalition, Early Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701183094 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1100 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0701183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Romanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During today's news conference of the Democratic 
Convention of Romania [CDR], CDR Chairman Emil Constantinescu 
presented the stance of that political alliance with respect to 
the evolution of the domestic political affairs over the past 
weeks, our correspondent, Iulia Gherman, reports. 
  After emphasizing the fact that, owing to the self-willed 
and 
rigid stance adopted by the ruling coalition, the political 
dialogue is currently blocked, Constantinescu pointed out that 
there are only two ways to overcome this situation, namely 
either the establishment of a new parliamentary majority or the 
holding of early elections. Talking about the first alternative, 
he asserted that the CDR will solely participate in the 
government together with the Social Democracy Party of Romania 
[PDSR] if the latter political grouping gets rid of the 
extremist parties and adopts a concrete anticrisis program. 
Related to the issue of holding early elections, Constantinescu 
said that this represents a constitutional and democratic method 
to solve the crisis caused by the lack of confidence in the 
current state power. If that solution will be really selected, 
that will be a direct consequence of the policy totally lacking 
imagination that is being promoted by the ruling party and its 
allies. 
  Constantinescu mentioned the fact that, tomorrow, the CDR 
Executive Council will meet in a conference to debate issues 
related to the current political, economic, and social situation 
in the country in view of the talks that are to be held on 
Tuesday [11 January] at Cotroceni Palace among President Ion 
Iliescu and CDR leaders. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

