<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sainovic, British Officials Discuss Sanctions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001223894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2221 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001223894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, January 10 (TANJUG) -- The sanctions 
imposed by the international community against the Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia do not help restore peace in the former 
Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina and secure an equal 
treatement for all the three confronted sides there, Prime 
Minister of the Yugoslav Republic of Serbia Nikola Sainovic said 
on Monday [10 January]. He said this during talks with three 
British MPs who are currently visiting Yugoslavia and the 
Bosnian Serb republic, the Republican Ministry of Information 
said in a statement. 
  In May 1992, the United Nations Security Council imposed 
tough sanctions against the Yugoslav republics of Serbia and 
Montenegro because of their alleged involvement in the civil war 
among Moslems, Serbs and Croats in Bosnia-Herzegovina. The 
allegation that only Serbia is responsible for the war in Bosnia 
is not correct, one of the British MPs, Nigel Evans, said in an 
interview to Serbian Television after the meeting with Sainovic. 
He also said he would present this view to the British 
Government. 
  The talks focused on the effects of the sanctions and the 
possibilities for unhindered and speedier delivery of British 
humanitarian medical supplies to Yugoslavia, he said. We are 
especially interested in working in that direction after our 
visits to hospitals where we saw the effects of the sanctions, 
Evans said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

