<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Protests NATO's `Anti-Serb' Efforts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001195494 Paris AFP in English 1928 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Jan 10 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb leader 
Radovan Karadzic on Monday [10 January] warned that a NATO 
threat to launch air strikes to lift the siege of Sarajevo could 
jeopardize the overall peace process for the region. 
  His comments came as North Atlantic Treaty Organization 
leaders, meeting at a summit in Brussels, discussed the 
possibility of renewing their threat of air strikes, originally 
made last year. 
  In a statement to the Bosnian Serb SRNA news agency, he 
warned against an "anti-Serb resolution" by NATO, saying that 
air strikes would only create "new difficulties." In particular 
he said that if NATO agreed to any resolution "against the 
Serbs" they would be forced to review territorial offers to 
Bosnian Moslems -- a key factor in the overall peace settlement. 
  "We offered 33.3 percent of the territory of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina to the Moslems, and accepted under certain 
conditions that Sarajevo be put under UN administration," he 
said. Karadzic said that, of the three warring sides, Bosnian 
Serbs had "proved to be the most cooperative." 
  He once again blamed the international community for the 
crisis in former Yugoslavia, saying it "would do nothing but 
continue its series of mistakes" if it continued to press its 
"anti-Serb" policies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

