<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic: No Changes in Peace Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001212794 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2100 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1001212794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Interview with Radovan Karadzic, president of the republic 
of Srpska, by Slobodan Kovacevic; place and date not given -- 
recorded] 
  [Text] [Kovacevic] Mr. President, you have briefed the 
deputies about the course of the peace talks to date. Is the 
Serbian side changing anything in the platform for the 
continuation of the talks in Geneva? 
  [Karadzic] For the time being we are not changing anything. 
We do not wish to add to any sort of confusion in hope that a 
peaceful solution will be found. We will leave it until the 
18th [January], perhaps the 17th, or perhaps even after the 
18th, in order to orient ourselves toward the future situation 
that will result from the Muslim-Croatian talks. 
  I would like to say that we have nothing against the 
Izetbegovic-Tudjman meeting in Bonn if this will contribute 
toward their reconciliation, which would help the overall peace 
in the entire Bosnia-Herzegovina. However, if Germany tries to 
reconciliate the Muslims and the Croats and turn them against 
the Serbs, we will oppose this, naturally. For this reason we 
do not wish to contribute to any sort of disruption of the 
constructive atmosphere and will wait to see how the events 
develop. 

</TEXT>

