<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik Welcomes NATO Decisions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101142394 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1327 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Obrenovac, 11 Jan (TANJUG) -- We welcome the 
decisions of the Atlantic alliance which, despite the 
Franco-British initiative to exert pressure on the Serbs, has 
given priority to the negotiating process, Momcilo Krajisnik, 
president of the assembly of the republic of Srpska, told Radio 
Obrenovac today. 
  Although we continue to have a critical stance vis-a-vis 
some 
NATO moves, we do not conceal our satisfaction at the fact that 
the "Sixteen" in Brussels have advocated negotiations -- 
something we have been in favor of from the very beginning, 
Krajisnik added. 
  He pointed out that the Serb side will continue to reject 
any 
planned resolutions that might imperil the strategic interests 
of the Serbian people. 
  Commenting on the possibility of the withdrawal of the "blue 
helmets" from the former Bosnia-Herzegovina, Krajisnik said that 
UN forces ought to remain until peace is achieved. 
  He added that the Serbs will not protest if the 
peace-keeping 
forces withdraw, because, he added, they have not been 
protecting the Serbs in any case, but the Muslims. 
  He recalled that it was with this protection that the 
Muslims 
had armed themselves. Peace could be achieved more easily and 
quickly, according to Krajisnik, if such support were withheld 
from the Muslims. 

</TEXT>

