<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Humanitarian Airlift Resumes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101095594 Paris AFP in English 0929 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, Jan 11 (AFP) -- The UNHCR humanitarian 
airlift to Sarajevo resumed on Tuesday morning after a break of 
almost a week because of shelling around the Bosnian capital's 
airport. 
  The first plane to land, an American C-130, touched down at 
0645 GMT, an official for the UN High Commissioner for Refugees, 
Kris Janowski, said. 
  He said 21 flights were expected during the day. 
  Usually between 25 and 27 planes daily bring in food, 
medicine and cold weather supplies, according to Captain Joel 
Fouquet, who is in charge of the 250 UN troops controlling the 
airport. 
  The UN Protection Force would like to up that to 40 a day, 
but "the Serbs are opposed to it," Fouquet told a press 
conference. 
  Nearly 90,000 tonnes of supplies have been unloaded from 
more 
than 8,000 flights into Sarajevo since the airlift started, he 
said. 

</TEXT>

