<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Olechowski Cautiously Welcomes Peace Partnership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001142494 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1326 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 10 Jan--An insufficient step in the right 
direction. This is how Foreign Minister Andrzej Olechowski 
summed up the discussion on Partnership for Peace at Monday's 
government meeting, which preceded the Prague summit of the 
Visegrad Group. 
  Olechowski said that the Council of Ministers "welcomed the 
Partnership for Peace as an interesting initiative that goes in 
the right direction" and authorized the prime minister to 
support this program. 
  The government assessed the decisions that are expected from 
the Brussels NATO summit (reassurance concerning the U.S. 
presence in Europe, the opening of NATO to new members in an 
evolutionary process, Partnership for Peace, and a definition of 
new relations between NATO and the Western European Union) as 
favorable from the point of view of Poland's interests, but it 
has reservations because they are not specific enough. 
  President Lech Walesa, who took part in the meeting, left 
the 
Office of the Council of Ministers without making any comment to 
the press. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49451 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu007_p_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-007 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

