<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Michnik Bemoans `Wasted' Opportunity of Visegrad </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0701200394 Warsaw GAZETA WYBORCZA in Polish 6 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU0701200394 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw GAZETA WYBORCZA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Untitled commentary by Adam Michnik] </F>
  [Text] It seemed as if our countries had learned from the 
bitter experience of Munich, Yalta, and the Brezhnev Doctrine, 
which permitted the making of decisions about Poland's fate 
without Poland's participation. It seemed that Visegrad would 
change all this. 
  Visegrad was also a chance for stability in the center of 
Europe. It could have become a real partner for the powerful 
countries. It enjoyed excellent reviews. 
  But it did not last long. The disintegration of 
Czechoslovakia was the first blow to Visegrad. Then 
Slovak-Hungarian conflicts broke out. And then politicians, not 
just in the Czech Republic, decided that they would reach Europe 
sooner if they went alone. 
  It looks like the greatest political chance of the Poles, 
Czechs, Slovaks, and Hungarians in the 20th century may be 
wasted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

