<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Shows Popularity of Prime Minister Pawlak </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001203594 Warsaw PAP in English 2005 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001203594 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan. 10 -- Some 55 percent of respondents to 
a poll conducted by the Public Opinion Polling Centre (OBOP) 
reported that they were rather fond of Waldemar Pawlak. 46 
percent liked Primate Jozef Glemp, while 45 percent were 
positively disposed towards Ombudsman Tadeusz Zielinski. 
  Other popular politicians are Jacek Kuron (39 percent of the 
poll respondents), Aleksander Kwasniewski (36 percent), Hanna 
Suchocka (35 percent), Andrzej Olechowski (31 percent), Jozef 
Oleksy (30 percent), Wlodzimierz Cimoszewicz (28 percent) and 
Ryszard Bugaj (24 percent). 
  50 percent of the poll respondents were not sure what it is 
exactly that Michal Strak (head of the cabinet office), Marek 
Borowski (deputy prime and finance minister) and Aleksander 
Luczak (deputy prime and education minister) do. 
  48 percent dislike Centre Alliance (PC) leader Jaroslaw 
Kaczynski, 39 percent -- Lech Walesa, while 38 percent are 
rather ill disposed to Confederation for an Independent Poland 
leader (KPN) -- Leszek Moczulski. 

</TEXT>

