<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prague Citizens Look Forward to Clinton Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001174094 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1600 
GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Public opinion polls are geared to the coming visit 
of U.S. President Bill Clinton. Ilona Dientsbierove has more 
details. 
  [Dienstbierova] The DEMA joint-stock company has prepared a 
series of questions concerning President Clinton's visit, 
targeted at 300 respondents from all Prague districts. 
  Some 63 percent of Prague citizens are looking forward to 
this visit, and 60 percent view it as an appreciation of current 
developments in our country. Approximately 50 percent of the 
respondents consider the visit by the U.S. President to be an 
expression of appreciation for President Vaclav Havel. 
Approximately the same percentage of the respondents consider 
this event to be an important step that should lead to the 
strengthening of trade and economic relations between the Czech 
Republic and the United States. It is interesting to note that 
approximately half of the respondents were unable to answer the 
questions. 
  The DEMA company was also interested in President Clinton's 
popularity among Prague citizens. According to the survey, the 
pattern of his popularity is relatively the same in all age 
groups. However, women are looking forward to his visit to a 
greater extent than men, by 67 percent to 59 percent. 

</TEXT>

