<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jeszensky Sees Partnership as `Road to NATO' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101115894 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1100 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101115894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The subject of the usual weekly press briefing by 
the Hungarian Foreign Ministry was the summit of the Visegrad 
Group of countries. Geza Jeszenszky's ideas, which he outlined 
before leaving [for the Prague meeting], have been summed up by 
Jozsef Barath. 
  [Barath] The series of meetings in Prague and the 
negotiations of leaders of the Visegrad states with President 
Clinton and with each other will strengthen the cooperation of 
the Visegrad Group members -- cooperation which derives from the 
shared fate of the Central European countries. This was said by 
[Foreign Minister] Geza Jeszenszky at his news briefing, which 
is still in progress. 
  In the foreign minister's view, the Partnership for Peace is 
one of the important stages on the road to NATO. The current 
NATO summit is similar in significance to the decisions in 
Copenhagen last summer on the long-term possibility of joining 
the European Union. Geza Jeszenszky emphasized that the current 
summit dispelled anxieties about the possibility that NATO's 
function might cease. The North Atlantic Treaty Organization has 
fulfilled the security vacuum which has developed in our region, 
he said. 
  The foreign minister welcomed President Clinton's 
confirmation that the United States has important interests 
linked to Central Europe. The 16 NATO states pledged their 
support for NATO's expansion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

