<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus: Need for `Real' Cooperation in U.S. Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1001205294 Prague CT 1 Television Network in Czech 1830 
GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1001205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CT 1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] Madelaine Albright and John 
Shalikashvili started their talks in Prague by meeting Prime 
Minister Vaclav Klaus. The content of the talks was aimed at 
assessing the U.S. project Partnership for Peace. According to 
the prime minister, the project is valued by the Czech 
Government for the broad and liberal approach it offers its 
participants. U.S. interest in the development of regional 
cooperation, which, according to Madelaine Albright, is as 
important as the Czech Republic's good relations with the United 
States, was also debated. 
  [Begin Klaus recording] I think the American side 
understands 
that if we protest sometimes it is rather a protest against 
certain empty regionalism, against artificial concepts that lead 
nowhere. As for real and good regional relations, we, I believe, 
say clearly yes. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

