<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties, Officials Comment on `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<H4>   SDRP Presents Position </H4>
<F P=102> LD0801173194 Warsaw PAP in English 1646 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0801173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan. 8 -- "In times of an extremely complex 
international situation and in conditions when the old world 
order no longer exists, there is an urgent need to create a new 
concept of security system, both the global and European one," 
the presidium of the main board of the Social Democracy of the 
Republic of Poland (SDRP) said Saturday presenting its stand on 
the "Partnership for Peace" plan. 
  The SDRP Presidium stressed such a system should not be 
aimed 
against anybody but has to function effectively in order to 
solve the existing conflicts and counteract potential threats 
and international crises. 
  In this context, the SDRP said it supported Poland's 
strivings for joining NATO and added that from the point of view 
of Poland's interests it considered the "Partnership for Peace" 
a step in the right direction though not a fully sufficient one. 
The SDRP said that the initiative needs to be appropriately 
specified and Poland should actively participate in this process. 
  "We believe that the content of the "Partnership for Peace," 
which will be specified with the participation of all the 
interested parties, will produce a system of mutual links which 
will provide solid foundations for a common and effective 
security system on the European continent. We are aware of the 
significance of Russia's participation in this extremely 
important process," the SDRP said and added that it was 
particularly important to create a favourable and constructive 
political climate around the initiative so that the "Partnership 
for Peace" plan could ensure security and stability of 
democratic development to the states participating in the 
process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

