<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties, Officials Comment on `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<H4>   KPN Leader Opposes Plan </H4>
<F P=102> LD1001163894 Warsaw PAP in English 1558 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1001163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan. 10 -- Leader of the Confederation for 
an Independent Poland (KPN) Leszek Moczulski said Monday that 
Poland's possible acceptance of the "Partnership for Peace" 
programme means "deluding oneself." 
  Moczulski proposed that Poland should rather take care of 
its 
own Armed Forces. According to Moczulski, Poland's policy 
related to the NATO membership has focused on reaching certain 
propagandist goals. It produced no positive results in the past 
several years but halted the country's defence preparations. 
  "One should have at least rebuilt the army to make it 
capable 
of counteracting threats we may encounter," Moczulski said. 

</TEXT>

