<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   PDSR Leader Comments on Early Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU0401190994 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 1724 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0401190994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, ROMPRES 4/1/1994 -- The executive 
President of the (ruling) Social Democracy Party of Romania 
(PDSR), Adrian Nastase, said that President Ion Iliescu's 
consultations with political leaders were useful for finding the 
best political solutions and formulae as a preliminary phase 
towards a political pact, prior to reaching a ruling pact. 
  Adrian Nastase is of the opinion that the transition to the 
new phase would be possible only when the political parties have 
formed "a certain idea of what a parliamentary majority means." 
The executive president of the PDSR also said at the press 
conference of Tuesday, 4 January, that President Iliescu could 
not possibly draw a new parliamentary map, because the present 
one was the result of the electoral process, but that he could 
endorse subsequent agreements between parties relying on the 
political pact in principle which can forego a possible 
discussion about the formation of a new parliamentary majority, 
and, consequently, of a new government. 
  While reasserting the openness to dialogue with other 
political parties, for a wider parliamentary support, Adrian 
Nastase said that if his party fails to obtain it so, it might 
consider the variant of withdrawing its confidence in the 
government and of switching to the opposition ranks. The 
recourse to early elections is accepted by his party, Mr. Adrian 
Nastase said, only as an ultimate solution, because the chances 
of having the present parliamentary representation proportions 
changed are very low, as a recent IRSOP [Romanian Institute for 
Opinion Polling] poll shows, he said, adding that this choice 
might present the risk that a low voting rate could raise doubts 
as to the legitimacy of the future legislative forum of Romania. 

</TEXT>

