<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Ethnic Hungarians Meeting in Komarno </TI></H3>
<H4>   Rally Formulates Minority Demands </H4>
<F P=102> AU1001200694 Prague CTK in English 2008 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Komarno, south Slovakia, Jan 8 (CTK) -- In spite of 
the original appeal by the Association of Towns and Villages of 
Zitny Ostrov (ZMOZO), the meeting of Hungarian ethnic minority 
representatives did not elect representatives of Hungarians, 
instead the minority's demands will be pushed for by deputies. 
  The meeting resulted in the adoption of declarations which 
call for solving ethnic problems and establishing relations 
between Slovaks and Hungarians on new principles. "The 
government's previous steps contributed to the worsening of 
mutual relations," the declaration writes. 
  The meeting asked to embody the collective rights of the 
Hungarian minority in the Slovak Constitution. It deemed 
necessary for the development of the Hungarian entity the use of 
the Hungarian language in administrative contact at any place 
where Hungarians make up at least one-tenth of the population. 
Hungarian should become, along with Slovak, the official 
language in locations with a Hungarian majority. The 
representation of Hungarians in state bodies and public 
institutions should be in line with their number. The Hungarian 
entity should be allotted a relevant share of state budget. The 
political existence of the minority should be expressed in the 
election of its own representative bodies. 
  The meeting expressed a claim to the "attribution of special 
legal status for territory with a large number of Hungarians." 
The implementation of ethnic rights in places where they 
constitute a minority should be based on the principle of 
mutuality. 
  Only two meeting participants voted against the 
declarations. 
The crowded arena applauded them because of their courage. The 
meeting also passed an open letter to the Slovak president and 
Slovak citizens, asking them to open a dialogue based on 
equality, and an appeal to Hungarian parents to send their 
children only to Hungarian schools. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49488 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu007__a94034" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-007-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 January 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Ethnic Hungarians Meeting in Komarno </TI></H3>
<H4>   Minority Leaders Comment </H4>
<F P=102> AU1001200794 Prague CTK in English 1534 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001200794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Komarno, Jan 9 (CTK) -- The leaders of the 
Hungarian minority in Slovakia are convinced that the demands 
formulated at yesterday's meeting here are realizable, "as long 
as the Slovak Government and parliament do not see democracy as 
the dictates the majority," said Miklos Duray, chairman of the 
Egyutteles (Coexistence) Movement, at a press conference after 
the meeting. 
  "We do not want to declare territorial autonomy, but to 
economically develop southern Slovakia," said Istvan Pasztor, 
chairman of the Association of Towns and Villages of Zitny 
Island and mayor of Komarno, on the demands of the Hungarian 
minority. 
  Ethnic Hungarians do not want "anything but to have the same 
rights as are extended to other, purely Slovak regions," said 
Vojtech Bugar, chairman of the Hungarian Christian Democratic 
Movement (MKDH), on the proposal to create new 
territorial-administrative units in southern Slovakia, where 
ethnic Hungarians make up a majority of the population. 
  Duray expressed the conviction that after yesterday's 
meeting, the Slovak Government and Parliament would not act 
against the principles of the European Charter of the Rights of 
Minorities and the Charter of Self-Government. He also said 
that he would strive for the revision of the Benes Decrees, 
under which ethnic Hungarians (as well as the Sudeten Germans) 
were expelled after World War II. 
  Regarding police inspections on the roads to Komarno before 
the meeting, which prevented several participants from 
attending, Bugar said that the Hungarian deputies in the Slovak 
parliament would make an interpellation with the interior 
minister. If it is determined that the minister gave the order 
to the police, or if he refuses to give an answer, Bugar said 
the deputies from Egyutteles and the MKDH would call for his 
removal. 

</TEXT>

