<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Ethnic Hungarians Meeting in Komarno </TI></H3>
<H4>   KDH Rejects `Ethnic Principle' </H4>
<F P=102> AU1001200294 Prague CTK in English 1550 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Jan 10 (CTK) -- The Christian 
Democratic Movement (KDH) does not consider the ethnic principle 
to be a chief criterion for establishing a new 
territorial-administrative set-up of Slovakia, as suggested by 
the meeting of ethnic Hungarian representatives, KDH Deputy 
Chairman Ivan Simko told CTK today. 
  The KDH does not deem it suitable to consider the use of 
Hungarian as official language in Slovakia, Simko said. It is 
necessary, however, to look for a feasible solution which would 
make it possible to use the mother tongue in administrative 
contact, he added. 
  Simko said that the Komarno, south Slovakia, meeting of 
January 8 had not contributed to straightening up of the 
relations between Slovaks and Hungarians. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

