<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Denies Allegation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001192194 Prague CTK in English 1237 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 10 (CTK) -- Security and Information 
Service (BIS) Director and former deputy director of the Federal 
Security and Information Service (FBIS) Ivan Devaty today 
dismissed as "not based on the facts" allegations that FBIS had 
actively worked against U.S. President Bill Clinton during the 
1992 presidential election campaign in the United States. 
  The statement by Basta and an unnamed FBIS officer was 
published by the Czech independent daily MLADA FRONTA DNES at 
the weekend. According to Basta, the Czechoslovak intelligence 
services provided incumbent President George Bush's election 
staff with information about Clinton's stay in Prague in 1970 
and interviewed his acquaintances in Prague, looking for 
information to discredit him. 
  The unnamed FBIS officer had told the paper that information 
was recorded for Bush's staff not only regarding the fact that 
Clinton had visited Moscow shortly after the 1968 invasion of 
Czechoslovakia by Warsaw Pact troops, but also regarding details 
about Clinton's hosts in Prague, the daughter and son-in-law of 
early Czech communist and later reformer and Charter 77 
signatory Marie Svermova. 

</TEXT>

