<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Dismisses Polish President's Criticism </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001212494 Prague CTK in English 2012 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001212494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 10 (CTK) -- Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus, 
reacting to statements by Polish President Lech Walesa in 
today's LIDOVE NOVINY, said he would be a bad Czech politicians 
if he did not place the Czech interests above the joint aims, 
never formulated, of the Visegrad Four. 
  "I am very disappointed," Walesa told the paper. "In 
difficult times, solidarity is necessary," Walesa said. "But 
here, priority is given to some particular interest over common 
aims. In my opinion, (the Czech politicians) are committing a 
mistake which will cost all of us something. If the talks fail, 
we will have to say that the organizers are to be blamed. 
Slovaks, Hungarians, and Poles wanted a joint strategy. I even 
proposed that Vaclav Klaus presented the joint statement on 
behalf of the four countries. But I did not manage," Walesa 
stated. 
  Walesa is right in accusing the Czech Republic of placing 
Czech interests over the joint aims of the Visegrad countries, 
Klaus said, saying he thought that Walesa was also placing 
Poland's interests before the Visegrad Four's. The joint 
interests of the Visegrad Four are a common denominator of the 
four countries' interests, nothing more and nothing less, Klaus 
said. 
  "The offer to present a common position of the four 
countries 
Walesa is talking about was never conveyed to me. As a result, 
I could not have refused it," Klaus stated. 
  Klaus added that the Czech Republic had neither organized 
nor 
initiated the talks of U.S. President Bill Clinton with Visegrad 
Four representatives. The Czech Republic "only" gladly accepted 
the American initiative and welcomed the idea of holding the 
talks in Prague. Klaus said he could not see any reason why the 
talks should fail. 

</TEXT>

