<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Albright Meets With Officials on `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Klaus Sees `Opportunity' </H4>
<F P=102> AU1001182594 Prague CTK in English 1240 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001182594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 10 (CTK) -- The security of the Czech 
Republic and that of the Central European region is directly 
linked to the security of the United States, U.S. Ambassador to 
the U.N. Madeleine Albright told Klaus today. 
  During a meeting between Albright, head of U.S. Armed Forces 
John Shalikashvili, and Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus, the three 
participants held similar views on the "Partnership for Peace" 
project. 
  To the countries of the Central European region, it presents 
an open opportunity for establishing close military and 
political ties with NATO, according to the statement issued by 
the Premier's Office. The project is also a tool, according to 
Klaus, for strengthening the internal stability of the Central 
European region. 
  U.S. presence in Europe is important for democratic 
development and stability of the whole of Europe, Klaus said at 
the meeting, adding that the Czech Republic is interested in its 
neighbors' success and prosperity. The Czech Republic prefers 
concrete accords like the Central European Free Trade Agreement 
to summits and joint declarations, Klaus said. 

</TEXT>

