<H3> <TI>   Albright Meets With Officials on `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Baudys on `Maximum' Cooperation </H4>
<F P=102> AU1001182694 Prague CTK in English 1340 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Prague, Jan 10 (CTK) -- It will not be long 
before the Czech Republic becomes a NATO member state, Czech 
Defense Minister Antonin Baudys told journalists today after his 
meeting with U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. Madeleine Albright and 
head of U.S. Armed Forces John Shalikashvili. 
  The U.S. project Partnership for Peace has been formulated 
in 
such a way, Baudys said, as to offer an almost unbelievably wide 
choice from "zero cooperation to the closest possible 
cooperation," allowing bilateral adaptation between the Czech 
and NATO armed forces. 
  "Under the project, we want to achieve a maximum number of 
concrete military steps," Baudys said, adding that he believed 
this would make "all NATO members see that the Czech Republic is 
capable of accepting its share of responsibility for the 
European security." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

