<H3> <TI>   Albright Meets With Officials on `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Zieleniec Cites `Important Step' </H4>
<F P=102> AU1001182794 Prague CTK in English 1434 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001182794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Prague, January 10 (CTK) -- The United States 
would welcome a common standpoint from the Visegrad countries 
(the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Poland, and Hungary) on the 
Brussels NATO summit, U.S. Ambassador to the UN Madeleine 
Albright said today after meeting Czech Foreign Minister Josef 
Zieleniec. Also present was John Shalikashvili, chairman of the 
Joint Chiefs of Staff of the U.S. Armed Forces. [passage omitted] 
  Albright and Shalikashvili informed Czech representatives on 
the political principles and individual aspects of the U.S. 
Partnership for Peace initiative, Czech Foreign Minister Josef 
Zieleniec said after a meeting with them today. 
  He stressed that the Czech Republic considered Partnership 
for Peace as a project which could bring new impulses to the 
creation of European security framework. The Czech Republic 
intends to show its partners that it is not striving just to 
acquire unilateral security guarantees, but that it is able to 
assume the relevant share of responsibility, Zieleniec said. 
  Zieleniec called the American initiative an important step 
which opened up the way for the Czech Republic to NATO. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

