<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Meet With Clinton, Comment on Plan </TI></H3>
<H4>   Olechowski Notes `Doubts' </H4>
<F P=102> LD1101233894 Warsaw Third Program Radio Network in Polish 
2300 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101233894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Third Program Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] I still have not dispelled all my doubts concerning 
the conviction that the Partnership for Peace leads to NATO 
membership, Andrzej Olechowski, head of the Polish diplomatic 
delegation, has said in Prague. In Olechowski's view, all the 
decisions made at the Brussels' summit were, after all, 
beneficial for Poland. In his opinion the Partnership for Peace 
raises the security level in such a sense that it brings us 
closer to NATO. Among other things, we will have access to the 
procedures and military technology of the pact. In time, we 
gradually will be getting access to early warning systems and 
the exchange of intelligence available to the pact, Olechowski 
said. 
  However, because of the fact that no timetable was defined 
for Poland joining western structures, Olechowski said that he 
considered it to be a Polish failure connected with the NATO 
summit in Brussels. 

</TEXT>

