<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Meet With Clinton, Comment on Plan </TI></H3>
<H4>   Ministers Continue Bilateral Talks </H4>
<F P=102> LD1201113694 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1000 
GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bilateral talks between Visegrad Four prime 
ministers continue in Hrzan Palace in Prague. Our editor Jana 
Zemanova is at Hrzan Palace. 
  [Zemanova] The meeting behind closed doors between the Czech 
and Slovak Prime Ministers Vaclav Klaus and Vladimir Meciar is 
drawing to an end in Hrzan Palace. It is a part of today's 
series of bilateral talks on security and further cooperation 
between Visegrad countries at prime ministerial level. 
  During the previous meeting between Czech Prime Minister 
Klaus and his Polish counterpart Waldemar Pawlak, the two 
politicians explained to each other a certain tension which was 
generated by Prague's individualist attitude to the acceptance 
of the U.S. Partnership for Peace plan. This is how Klaus 
described this situation: 
  [Begin Klaus recording] I think that relations are not as 
tense as it would appear from some media headlines. We have a 
whole number of projects we would like to execute together. 
These projects should be directed at practical forms of 
Czech-Polish contacts and cooperation. I think that our views 
on this point were completely identical. [end recording] 
  [Zemanova] What is important is that the two prime ministers 
jointly emphasized the willingness to continue to cooperate and 
to meet for further talks as soon as possible. According to 
Pawlak, economic cooperation will have priority in future 
relations between the Czech Republic and Poland. After all, 
this can be documented by the presence at the talks of Czech 
Economics Minister Karel Dyba. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

