<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials Meet With Clinton, Comment on Plan </TI></H3>
<H4>   Olechowski on `Innovative' Plan </H4>
<F P=102> LD1201125094 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1100 
GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Let us go back to Prague Castle once again. 
Czech radio correspondent Eva Hulkova has recorded several 
statements there. [passage omitted] 
  The next speaker to come to the Czech radio microphone was 
Polish Foreign Minister Andrzej Olechowski. 
  [Begin Olechowski recording, in English fading into Czech 
translation] What we are saying is that we regard the 
Partnership for Peace as a very important contribution to 
European security. We think it is an innovative, constructive, 
and optimistic program. As we have often been saying, our 
problem with this program is that, although it is a step in the 
right direction, it is a very small step, because this program 
does not provide a clear prospect for our NATO membership. We 
have noticed, unfortunately, that in all the Western 
institutions in which we are seeking membership, there are 
various stages of preparation for our membership. No promise 
has been given to us that we will actually get this membership. 
This is where the essence of Polish criticism lies. [end 
recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

