<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO To Consider Bosnian Membership </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101203594 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1101203594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner replied to 
the letter he received from Irfan Ljubijankic, foreign minister 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina, on 23 December 1993 concerning our 
initiative for Bosnia-Herzegovina's participation in the 
Partnership for Peace. The letter stresses that 
Bosnia-Herzegovina's application will be considered and that all 
NATO members have been informed about this initiative. 
  Partnership for Peace does not represent formal membership 
in 
NATO. It implies mutual obligations of NATO member states and 
those countries whose foreign and defense policies have the same 
aims as those of NATO member states. This idea was initiated by 
U.S. President Bill Clinton and, in the initial stage, it 
referred to some Central European countries that have already 
met the conditions for participation in Partnership for Peace. 
In his letter to Ljubijankic, Woerner expressed the belief that 
this year will bring peace to Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  This was stated in a communique issued by the Foreign 
Ministry of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

