<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Failure' of NATO Air Strike Proposal Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101162594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1605 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101162594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item -- by Stevan Cordas] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, January 11 (TANJUG) -- The failure of the 
French-British proposal presented at the NATO summit in Brussels 
for threatening the Bosnian Serbs with air strikes if they 
refuse to allow the use of the Tuzla airport and lift the 
blockade of the Moslem enclave of Srebrenica was a logical and 
expected outcome of the meeting, diplomatic sources in Belgrade 
assessed in first unofficial reactions on Tuesday. 
  This opinion is based on NATO's old stand that only a 
political solution is possible in the former Yugoslav Republic 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina, as it was again stressed at the two-day 
summit. 
  This is precisely why NATO is using threats and pressure to 
stimulate the three warring sides in Bosnia to lay down arms and 
find political solutions to their conflicts. 
  The harsh threats made by NATO officials prior to the 
Brussels summit were calculated to step up pressure in 
expectation of a new round of peace talks on Bosnia, due to open 
in Geneva on January 18, and before the talks between Croatian 
President Franjo Tudjman and Bosnian Moslem leader Alija 
Izetbegovic in Bonn last Sunday and Monday, the sources said. 
  The strongest threats were again addressed to the Bosnian 
Serb side while the Croats were threatened with sanctions and 
the Moslems with a withdrawal of the United Nations peacekeepers 
from Bosnia. 
  The Brussels summit has shown that the Bosnian conflict is 
indeed giving NATO a headache but that it is by no means its 
main preoccupation. 
  No doubt, the organization finds the questions of Russia, 
NATO's survival and other issues relating to its operation more 
vital than the problem of Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49522 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu008aa_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-008 </AU>
