<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac Addresses Message to Army Members </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101173294 Bratislava REPUBLIKA in Slovak 4 Jan 94 pp 1,2 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101173294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava REPUBLIKA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [TA SR report: "Slovakia Will Not Become a Toy in the Hands </F>
of the Strong"] 
  [Excerpt] Trencin -- A festive rally of Army of the Slovak 
Republic commanders was held in Trencin yesterday, on the 
occasion of the beginning of the second year of the existence of 
the Slovak Republic and the building of the Army of the Slovak 
Republic. It was attended by Defense Minister Imrich Andrejcak, 
Army Commander Lieutenant General Julius Humaj, and senior 
members of the Army of the Slovak Republic Officers' Corps. 
  At the outset of the rally, its participants heard a letter 
addressed by President Michal Kovac to the participants in the 
rally. The letter states, among other things, that in the 
security and political spheres, we are oriented unequivocally 
toward NATO and the West European Union (WEU). We are looking 
for guarantees to ensure that Slovakia will never again become a 
toy in the hands of the strong. 
  As Michal Kovac went on to stress, according to ideas 
communicated by former U.S. Defense Secretary Les Aspin, 
participation by the Slovak Republic, along with the other 
states of the Visegrad Group, in the Partnership for Peace 
initiative should serve as an intermediary organizational link 
on the road toward fully fledged NATO membership. This should 
mean the possibility of achieving a certain type of associate 
membership of NATO or the WEU. According to Michal Kovac, this 
would not require full integration of the military components, 
but should at least contain guarantees that the parties will be 
consulted whenever the territorial integrity, political 
independence, or security of either party will be jeopardized, 
in the opinion of one of them. 
  In another part of his letter, Michal Kovac appreciated the 
fact that, in defiance of complicated conditions, the division 
of the former Federal Army has been completed in a relatively 
short period of time. He assured Army members that he will see 
to it that all necessary conditions be established for the Army 
of the Slovak Republic to discharge its duties and for it to be 
accorded such a degree of social recognition as corresponds to 
the nature and significance of its work for the benefit of the 
Slovak Republic. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

