<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Coalition Supports, Communists Oppose U.S. Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101224894 Prague Stanice Praha Radio Network in Czech 
2130 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101224894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Stanice Praha Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The coalition parties [the Civic Democratic Party, 
the Civic Democratic Alliance, the Christian Democratic 
Union--Czechoslovak People's Party, and the Christian Democratic 
Party] assess positively the U.S. project Partnership for Peace, 
which was approved by the top officials of NATO countries in 
Brussels yesterday [10 January]. 
  The Czech Social Democratic Party and the Liberal Social 
National Party are also positive about the project. All of the 
above consider this project to be, first of all, the first step 
to the desirable cooperation of the Czech Republic with NATO. 
  The Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia and the Left Bloc 
disagree with this opinion. They warn against our joining NATO 
because they see a possible isolation in relation to the 
remaining partners within the Visegrad Four, as well as the 
threat of cutting down on our sovereignty. 

</TEXT>

