<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa Says Partnership for Peace Unsatisfactory </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1201102994 Warsaw RZECZPOSPOLITA in Polish 12 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> WS1201102994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw RZECZPOSPOLITA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by M.W.: "Imposed Partnership"] </F>
  [Text] "The Partnership for Peace" program thrust upon 
Poland does not satisfy it," declared President Walesa on the 
eve of his meetings with U.S. President Bill Clinton and the 
leaders of the Czech Republic, Slovakia, and Hungary in Prague 
on 12 January. 
  Asked if Poland seeks full membership in NATO or only its 
security guarantees, the president said that "paper guarantees" 
are good for nothing. An authentic security guarantee would be 
Poland's integration into European structures, including NATO. 
Walesa thinks that his meeting with the U.S. President will be 
"difficult" because Clinton will probably defend his program, 
which is kind of imposed on us. 
  President Walesa will fly to Prague at 0615 GMT on 12 
January, while Prime Minister Pawlak departs 45 minutes before 
the president. That same day in the evening, also separately, 
both politicians will return to Warsaw. According to the 
Belvedere and the URM [Council of Ministers Administration], the 
top state officials cannot travel together. The president and 
prime minister will be accompanied by Foreign Minister Andrzej 
Olechowski, who is already in Prague to prepare the meeting with 
Clinton and U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher. The 
Polish delegation will first meet with Czech officials, and then 
with the Americans. 
  During his meeting with Edward Moskal, chairman of the 
Congress of Polish Americans, Deputy Prime Minister Aleksander 
Luczak thanked him for the support extended by that organization 
for Poland's seeking full NATO membership. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

