<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sejm Deputies May Vote Against Draft Budget </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801213694 Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network in 
Polish 1830 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0801213694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw TVP Television First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Relayed by Warsaw TV Polonia Network] </F>
  [Excerpts] The Sejm debate on the government draft budget 
has revealed that both in the Polish Peasant Party [PSL] and in 
the Democratic Left Alliance [SLD] there are groups of deputies 
critical of actions being taken by Waldemar Pawlak's cabinet. 
If the commissions do not propose increased expenditure on 
agriculture and social welfare, 30 to 40 coalition deputies are 
prepared to vote against the budget. The coalition has, 
however, such a majority in the parliament that even a loss of a 
double this number of votes cannot undermine the government. 
  [Correspondent] The most dissatisfied are some National 
Trade 
Union Alliance [OPZZ] deputies, whose leader in the SLD 
parliamentary floor group is Stanislaw Wisniewski. Deputy 
Wisniewski is of the opinion that, if during work on the budget 
it is not possible to increase funding for social welfare, 
active combatting of unemployment, and restructuring of the most 
threatened regions, the OPZZ should vote against the budget. 
[passage omitted] 
  In the PSL, a group of about 20 deputies from the 
[organization of] agricultural circles is the most critical of 
the draft budget. The board [of the organization] instructed its 
parliamentarians to vote against the government if the funding 
for agriculture is not increased from 2 billion to 6 billion 
zlotys. Some PSL activists are of the opinion that the SLD 
coalition members want to discriminate against agriculture. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

