<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Departs for Visegrad, Clinton Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101200294 Bratislava STV 1 Television Network in Slovak 
1830 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101200294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava STV 1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] The delegation of the Slovak Republic, 
headed by President Michal Kovac, left the Bratislava airport by 
air for Prague late this afternoon. Shortly before his departure 
for a meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton and the highest 
representatives of the Visegrad Four, we asked Michal Kovac for 
his comment on the coming summit. 
  [Begin recording] [Kovac] We expect that President Clinton 
will inform us about the conclusions and offer, and we are ready 
to accept the offer within the framework of Partnership for 
Peace. We pledge ourselves that we will take immediate action so 
that we can conclude the relevant agreements. Naturally, this is 
also an opportunity for us to inform the United States about our 
endeavors here at home in the Slovak Republic to continue in the 
process of strengthening the plurality system of democracy, 
transformation, and economic reforms. As you know, at the same 
time this will also provide an opportunity for bilateral talks 
with representatives of the Visegrad Group. [end recording] 
  [Announcer] Other members of the delegation are Prime 
Minister Vladimir Meciar; Deputy Prime Ministers Jozef Prokes, 
Sergej Kozlik, and Julius Toth; Jozef Moravcik, minister of 
foreign affairs; Jan Ducky, minister of the economy; Irena 
Belohorska, minister of health; and Imrich Andrejcak, minister 
of defense. Ambassadors of the Slovak Republic to Prague and 
Washington Ivan Mjartan and Branislav Lichardus are also in the 
delegation. 

</TEXT>

