<H3> <TI>   Walesa Departs for Visegrad Talks in Prague </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201090594 Warsaw PAP in Polish 0637 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1201090594 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 12 Jan -- This morning, President Lech 
Walesa left Warsaw for Prague where he is to meet the leaders of 
the Visegrad Group and President Bill Clinton. Asked by 
journalists at Warsaw military airport whether his "propaganda 
offensive" has changed the position of western states, the 
president replied: "I think that no more can be done after the 
NATO summit in Brussels." The president added that world public 
opinion "should exert greater pressure on politicians not to 
repeat the same mistakes." "There are opportunities which have 
to be taken, agreements which have to be kept," the president 
said, adding that he hopes that in Prague "we do more for a more 
secure and more human future." 

