<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Says `Hardest Period' in Economy Over </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101184394 Prague CTK in English 0652 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101184394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, Jan 11 (CTK) -- Czech Premier Vaclav 
Klaus, in an interview with the U.S. television station PBS, 
rejected the view that the transformation of the Czech economy 
is yet to see its hardest period. 
  "It is simply an erroneous analysis, it is not true," Klaus 
said in the interview broadcast Monday [10 January]. He said 
this view is being voiced not only in the Czech Republic but 
often also in other post-communist countries which are slightly 
envious of the results the Czech Republic has achieved. No 
dramatic change as regards unemployment and bankrupts would take 
place, Klaus said, adding that this would be a continual 
process. "We are naturally expecting a certain increase in 
unemployment but it will be tenths of a percent, but not ten 
percent -- the difference between unemployment in the Czech 
Republic and, for example, in Poland," Klaus said. 
  He expressed satisfaction that U.S. President Bill Clinton 
would visit Central Europe and especially Prague. "This is an 
important symbol," Klaus said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

