<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pipeline Project Talks With Bavaria Fail </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101072294 Prague CTK in English 1746 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101072294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 10 (CTK) -- Czech Industry and Trade 
Minister Vladimir Dlouhy and Bavarian Minister of Economics and 
Transport Otto Wiesheu were not able to agree at their meeting 
today on providing guarantees against so-called acts of God that 
damage the Ingolstadt oil pipeline. Dlouhy said he and Wieshau 
were discussing what was already a second draft of an agreement, 
and that from here on a group of Czech and Bavarian experts 
would work on the problem. 
  Wieshau said Bavaria fully supported the pipeline project, 
but that the Czechs were the party with the primary interest in 
it. Those who own the land over which the pipeline will run want 
to know who will insure them against terrorist attacks, natural 
disasters, or other "acts of God," and it cannot be Bavaria, he 
said. He said a law on pipeline-landowner land rights had been 
worked out in the Bavarian Parliament, but that it needed to be 
passed by the October elections or "we will have to start from 
square one." 
  Construction of the pipeline from the Bavarian town of 
Ingolstadt to Nelahozeves u Kralup in central Bohemia began in 
the Czech Republic in September. Construction of the pipeline 
in Germany is expected to begin this spring. The entire project 
should be completed in 1995, but Wieshau said this depends on 
what happens in the parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49603 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu008__a94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-008-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 January 1994 </DATE1>

