<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communists Favor Treaties, Oppose NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101170194 Prague CTK in English 1437 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101170194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 11 (CTK) -- To enhance peace and 
security the Czech Republic should "conclude treaties of 
friendship and peaceful cooperation.... mainly with powers such 
as the United States, Germany, France, Great Britain, and 
Russia," Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia (KSCM) says in a 
letter addressed to U.S. President Bill Clinton and given to CTK 
today. 
  "Our experiences show that it is not the question of joint 
military exercises or the presence of foreign troops on our 
territory but genuine cooperation in the interest of peace, 
security, democracy, and economic prosperity which should be 
embedded in these treaties," the letter says. To fulfill these 
goals "collective consultative mechanisms of all countries 
concerned" should be strengthened. 
  Employees of the U.S. Embassy in Prague told CTK they could 
not confirm whether the letter was received by the embassy since 
"there were many letters addressed to the President." However, 
they said that Clinton would certainly get all the 
correspondence addressed to him. 
  KSCM Chairman Miroslav Grebenicek writes in the letter that 
communists recall with pleasure Clinton's first informal visit 
in Prague in 1970 where he stayed in his friend's house "with 
the family of hero of anti-fascist resistance and renowned 
left-oriented politician Jan Sverma." 
  From the position of one of the strongest Czech opposition 
parties the communists express their stand on Clinton's 
forthcoming talks in Prague and stress that the interests of the 
Czech Republic' security, sovereignty, national identity, and 
economic prosperity are their prime concern. 
  However, unlike official representatives, the communists do 
not believe that membership of NATO is the road to implementing 
these goals. "We have very bad experiences with the Europe of 
Cold War and military pacts" the letter stresses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

