<H3> <TI>   Pawlak Says Administration To Be Streamlined </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0801182294 Warsaw PAP in English 1754 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0801182294 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan. 8 -- When asked whether his government 
would continue the reform of the public administration started 
by the Hanna Suchocka cabinet, Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak 
said during a meeting with regional press newsmen Saturday that 
it would rather be "streamlining than reforming." 
  The prime minister criticized work on the district reform, 
stressing that the communes had not been consulted at all on 
whether districts were to be established. He said his cabinet 
was not aiming at the centralization of power and also stressed 
that the point was not to "centrally" shift responsibility on 
local governments. 
  Pawlak denied press statements according to which his 
cabinet 
sent an expert analysis of the concordat signed by the previous 
government to the Secretariat of Poland's Episcopate. He 
stressed the government was not conducting any work on the 
document. 
  Asked about possible changes at the posts of deputy 
ministers 
in the so-called presidential ministries, namely, the Ministries 
of Internal Affairs, National Defence and Foreign Affairs, the 
prime minister said the issue aroused too strong emotions. 
  The prime minister also announced actions designed to limit 
the so-called grey zone. 

</TEXT>

