<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Committee Reports 1.1 Million Unemployed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1101104394 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 0851 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1101104394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, ROMPRES, 11/01/94 -- Gorj, a southern 
county of Romania, reported the lowest unemployment rate as at 
the end of December 1993: 3.7 percent, the National Statistics 
Committee informs. 
  Following Gorj were Bucharest City with 5.5 percent, Brasov 
County with 6.7 and Timis with 6.9 percent. Other 23 counties 
reported rates below the all-nation average of 9.9 percent. 
  At the other end of the scale, Vaslui recorded the highest 
rate 22.1 percent, followed by Bistrita-Nasaud with 20.3 
percent, Tulcea 18.2, and Neamt 17.1 percent, all in the East of 
Romania. 
  The all-Romania registered jobless were 1.1 million persons, 
of whom 525,000 were on the unemployment benefit scheme, over 
509,000 were recipients of subsistence allowances, and another 
97,000 were on record as unemployed whose benefit rights were 
overdue. 

</TEXT>

