<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Returns From Israel, Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1001200094 Prague CTK in English 2128 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1001200094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Jan 7 (CTK) -- There is no open problem 
between Slovakia and Israel, Foreign Minister Jozef Moravcik 
told journalists on his return from a five-day visit to Israel 
and Cyprus. The Slovak delegation included Economics Minister 
Jan Ducky, Governor of the National Bank of Slovakia Vladimir 
Masar, and a number of businessmen. 
  During his three-day stay in Israel, Moravcik met with his 
Israeli counterpart, the Israeli premier, president and the 
speaker of the Knesset, the Israeli parliament. 
  The Slovak balanced diplomatic activity is aimed at 
"creating 
throughout the region equal opportunities and room for 
cooperation," Moravcik said, adding, "one of the prerequisites 
for this is the implementation of the peace agreement between 
Israel and the Palestinians." 
  In order to further bilateral cooperation, agreements on the 
prevention of double taxation and protection of investments have 
to be signed, he said. 
  His visit to Israel focused on the extension of political 
dialogue, bilateral trade, and areas of prospective cooperation. 
These are envisaged as agriculture, banking, travel industry, 
and Israeli investment in Slovakia. "The first stage of 
building bilateral ties logically culminated in this visit," 
Moravcik said. 

</TEXT>

