<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on `Partnership for Peace' Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meciar Praises `Partnership' Plan </H4>
<F P=102> LD1201162494 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1100 
GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201162494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Visegrad group prime ministers held bilateral 
meetings in Hrzan Palace in Prague. Ilona Dienstbierova covered 
their talks. 
  [Dienstbierova] [passage omitted] I will recall briefly the 
bilateral talks between Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus and 
Slovak Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar. The Slovak prime minister 
commented on the initial conditions of the countries that are to 
join the Partnership for Peace plan. 
  [Begin Meciar recording] We are equal in a political and 
legal sense, but not in reality. We are not equal in terms of 
the geopolitical situation and economic development. As far as 
the state and the level of building the Armed Forces is 
concerned, we are not on the same level either. That is why the 
Partnership for Peace, as a contractual principle and as a 
blueprint for doing things, is creating an opportunity and is 
initiating a certain process. The development of this process 
could take place (?on an individual basis). At the same time, 
the course of this process cannot be determined at present. 
This means that its outcome might be quite different, 
irrespective of the fact that things may appear to be a 
certainty today. 
  Thus, the Partnership for Peace plan has opened up a process 
which, we think, is providing an opportunity for us. Even 
though not all of us are on the same level as we stand here on 
the starting line, there is no way we can forecast as yet what 
the results will be. [end recording] [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

