<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on `Partnership for Peace' Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   Goncz Luncheon Speech Reported </H4>
<F P=102> LD1201160394 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1500 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201160394 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We have just received the text of the speech of 
Arpad Goncz, Hungarian head of state. Arpad Goncz considers it 
important that all those states which make efforts for the 
assertion of democracy, market economy, and human rights should 
be allowed to join the Partnership for Peace program. The 
president of the Hungarian Republic spoke at a working lunch in 
Prague, attended by the leaders of the United States and 
Visegrad countries. The head of state also pointed out that 
neither Russia, Ukraine, or any other state of the region can be 
excluded from the European security systems. 
  According to Arpad Goncz, President Bill Clinton's talks in 
Prague prove that the United States continues to be committed to 
Europe and the democracies of the Visegrad Group. 

</TEXT>

