<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on `Partnership for Peace' Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   Zieleniec Comments on Partnership </H4>
<F P=102> LD1301094494 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 0600 
GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1301094494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The highest Czech representatives -- the president, 
prime minister, and foreign minister -- hosted dinners for their 
Visegrad Group countries' counterparts. The foreign ministers, 
meeting at a dinner in the Cernin Palace, agreed that the 
Partnership for Peace is the first step toward integrating the 
Visegrad Group states into NATO, and that in the current 
conditions the security guarantees provided by the project are 
adequate. The Czech foreign minister confirmed this in an 
interview given to Czech Radio: 
  [Begin Zieleniec recording] I think that the Partnership for 
Peace is quite a step toward integrating our country into NATO 
and toward creating new security structures in Europe. We all 
know, not only from foreign politics but from everyday life, 
that when several partners negotiate then usually none of them 
immediately achieves everything he wants. 
  On the other hand, the preparation of this project has 
taught 
us an important lesson. From the moment the idea was first 
conceived, we have achieved substantial and truly important 
changes, through which an initially very raw and purely 
military-technological project has become something possessing a 
significant political dimension, something that can be 
interpreted only as a step toward integrating central European 
countries into the NATO security system. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

