<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Favors Pressuring Warring Parties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301134494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1309 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301134494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, January 13 (TANJUG) -- French Foreign 
Minister Alain Juppe urged Thursday [13 January] stepping up 
political pressure on all the three warring parties in Bosnia so 
peace agreement would be reached at the next round of the Geneva 
talks. In a statement to TANJUG Cairo correspondent, Juppe said 
the aim of France was to "exert strong political pressure on the 
warring sides in Bosnia" -- the Moslems, Serbs and Croats. 
  France, together with Great Britain, initiated at the recent 
NATO summit in Brussels that a threat with air strikes on the 
positions of the Bosnian Serbs be included in the final document 
if the Serbs resisted opening of the airport in Tuzla and 
prevented replacement of the U.N. troops in Srebrenica. Tuzla 
and Srebrenica have been declared safe areas and are situated in 
northeastern and eastern Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

