<H3> <TI>   Maribor Prosecutor Says Jansa Violated UN Embargo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1201192694 Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network in Slovene 
1430 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1201192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Let us continue our program with new developments 
regarding the Maribor arms affair. When expounding yesterday on 
some decisions by the Maribor Public Prosecutor's Office 
regarding the finding of arms at the Maribor airport, Dusan 
Pozar, senior prosecutor in the Maribor Public Prosecutor's 
Office, pointed out that the basic prosecutor's office worked 
according to law. Proof was insufficient to prove unauthorized 
dealing in arms, or to prove smuggling. According to the 
prosecutor, there is still the suspicion that the Defense 
Ministry has recognized Hasan Cengic as the authorized envoy of 
the former Bosnia-Herzegovina and traded in arms with him. This 
happened in spring 1992 when it sold him 5,560 automatic rifles 
in violation of the UN Security Council Resolution on the 
embargo on arms sale to the territory of the former Yugoslavia. 
According to the prosecutor, Janez Jansa, as the only competent 
person, has violated the Security Council Resolution several 
times. Therefore, the Maribor Public Prosecutor's Office has 
presented the matter to the Ljubljana Public Prosecutor's Office. 

</TEXT>

