<H3> <TI>   Muslims Skeptical of Air Raid Threat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1201143094 Paris AFP in English 1406 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201143094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, Jan 12 (AFP) -- Sarajevo's mainly Moslem 
population is skeptical about NATO's latest warning that it 
might attack Serb artillery positions in Bosnia-Herzegovina, the 
OSLOBODJENJE daily reported Wednesday. 
  The North Atlantic Treaty Organisation declaration on 
Tuesday 
is "not very clear and even contradictory," the paper said 
adding that "it carries no ultimatum, thus no firm decision to 
end Milosevic's campaign by the only possible means -- force." 
Slobodan Milosevic is the president of Serbia. 
  The paper added that the mainly Moslem Bosnian army "would 
suffer nothing but harm if it trusted the NATO threat" and that 
Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic has also dismissed the 
warning. The NATO declaration came at the end of the alliance's 
two-day summit Tuesday. 

</TEXT>

