<F P=102>  LD1101172194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1631 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1101172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Belgrade, 11 Jan (TANJUG) -- Deputy Serb Republic 
(RS) President Nikola Koljevic said today that during the talks 
yesterday with the Japanese diplomat Yasushi Akashi, the new 
head of the UN Protection Force [UNPROFOR] for the former 
Yugoslavia, and Francis Briquemont, the military commander of 
the peacekeeping forces for Bosnia-Herzegovina, the Serbs got 
assurances that there can be no military intervention without 
the consent of these high-ranking UN representatives, and that 
they "in no way favor a military option as something desirable 
or something with high priority." 
  In the Belgrade radio program "One Argument More" today, 
Koljevic said the Serbs, for their part, have offered everything 
demanded from them and have been cooperative, in the belief that 
this is the price of peace. [passage omitted] 

