<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   HVO Obstructs Aid Convoy to Maglaj </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1301135994 Paris AFP in English 1338 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1301135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, Jan 13 (AFP) -- Meanwhile Bosnian Croat 
HVO forces continued to prevent for the second day running a 
nine-truck aid convoy from entering the besieged Moslem town of 
Maglaj, UNHCR spokesman Janowski told journalists here. 
  The situation in the northern central town crammed with 
around 40,000 inhabitants and refugees was getting desperate, 
Janowski said, adding that no convoys had reached the town since 
October 25. Four U.S. planes dropped supplies over the town 
overnight Wednesday, UNPROFOR said. 
  The UNHCR convoy, which is carrying flour, sugar and 
medicine, is blocked at Novi Seher, around 10 kilometres (six 
miles) southwest of Maglaj, Janowski said. The town is 
surrounded on three sides by Bosnian Serb forces and on the 
fourth by HVO troops. 
  UNHCR official Larry Hollingworth was trying Thursday 
morning 
to negotiate a passage for the convoy with local HVO commanders. 
Bosnian Serb authorities had allowed the convoy to pass without 
hindrance, Janowski added. 
  The spokesman added that the hold-up had persuaded the UNHCR 
to delay the departure of another convoy destined for the Croat 
enclave of Zepce around 15 kilometres (nine miles) south of 
Maglaj. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49657 </DOCNO>
