<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akashi Begins UNPROFOR Envoy Mandate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1201221394 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1830 
GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1201221394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yasushi Akashi, the UN Secretary General Butrus 
Ghali's special envoy and UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] chief 
coordinator, stressed in his talks with the local press that at 
the moment, UNPROFOR's main problem in Croatia was the 
stabilization of the cease-fire, following which one can embark 
on the demilitarization of UN Protected Area zones and the 
implementation of other tasks within the protection force's 
mandate. The problem of the return of refugees, in his view, 
must wait for the materialization of a peace agreement. 
  Akashi stressed that the challenges facing UNPROFOR in 
Croatia were greater than those in Cambodia where he had worked 
with a UN peace mission. For, he said, the protection force in 
Croatia us working both on achieving and keeping peace. 
UNPROFOR can do more than it has done so far, Akashi said and 
added that Chapter Six of the UN Charter, under which his 
mandate in Croatia has taken place, provides sufficient 
potential, which have not been harnessed yet. 
  In this context, Akashi expects firm cooperation with the 
Croatian authorities and hopes that some past problems in their 
relations will be ironed out. Today, as he announced, Akashi 
will talk to Ambassador Gerd Ahrens, a mediator between the 
Croatian authorities and UN Protected Areas. The implementation 
in practice of the economic and communications reintegration of 
these areas in Croatia as a whole will be the main topic of 
their talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

