<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   IMF Not To Aid Drafting of Economic Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1101173494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1508 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1101173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, January 11 (TANJUG) -- The International 
Monetary Fund (IMF) will be unable to participate in the drawing 
up of the economic programme of the Federal Republic of 
Yugoslavia because of the "current circumstances," the 
organization has informed Yugoslav Prime Minister Radoje Kontic. 
  The director of the first IMF European department said in a 
letter that the organization was aware of the grave economic 
situation in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and especially 
of the need to focus on the settling of the serious economic 
problems but that the circumstances did not allow it to help 
Yugoslavia in its efforts. On December 28, Kontic asked the IMF 
to help draw up a new Yugoslav stablization programme. 
  The Yugoslav Government has in the meantime completed its 
own 
economic programme whose essence has not yet been explained to 
the public. A stabilization programme is urgently needed 
because Yugoslavia is currently under a complete economic 
blockade while its rampant inflation reached the official figure 
of one million percent in December. 
  In May 1992, the United Nations Security Council imposed 
tough economic sanctions against Yugoslavia accusing it of being 
involved in the civil war among Moslems, Serbs and Croats in the 
neighbouring former Yugoslav republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. As 
part of the economic sanctions, Yugoslavia's membership to the 
imf has been frozen. In conclusion, the IMF expressed hope in 
the letter that the circumstances would in the future allow the 
organization to open talks on support to Yugoslavia's 
stabilization programme. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

