<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Democratic Party Reports Harassment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1201163094 Belgrade BORBA in Serbo-Croatian 11 Jan 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU1201163094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade BORBA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [S.Z. attributed report: "`The Authorities are Resorting to </F>
Violence'"] 
  [Text] Belgrade -- The Democratic Party of Serbia [DSS] 
has warned the public that, in the period following the 
elections, prominent members of the party are increasingly being 
attacked. 
  According to a statement issued by the DSS Information 
Service, the chairman of the Communal Council in Vrsac was 
forced to defend his property himself after his business 
premises had been broken into several times and the police had 
failed to react. In Bujanovac, a DSS parliamentary candidate 
was brutally attacked and injured by Goran Veljkovic, son of the 
local strongman, Socialist Party of Serbia deputy Randjel 
Veljkovic, while in Surdulica -- claims the statement -- the 
local authorities have selectively and illegally seized the 
business premises belonging to the wife of the DSS Communal 
Council chairman in this town. 
  All these cases show -- the statement concludes -- that the 
authorities, instead of solving the vital problems that they 
have caused, are increasingly resorting to violence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49675 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu009_y_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-009 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Bread in Belgrade Due to Bakers Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301102294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 0951 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301102294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, January 13 (TANJUG) -- Nearly two million 
Belgrade residents could not buy bread Thursday morning [13 
January] as the city's central bakery went on strike. The 
bakers demanded they be paid in keeping with the defined minimum 
wages, the striking committee said. Bread deliveries were made 
only to hospitals and the Army. Negotiations were underway with 
the representatives of the authorities and if an accord was 
reached during the morning hours, the bakers would normalize 
production in the course of the day. 
  The strike of bakers, something even the oldest Belgraders 
do 
not remember, was only one in a series of strikes that hit the 
Yugoslav capital late last and early this year and which came as 
a result dissatisfaction with extremely low wages. Severe 
sanctions imposed by the U.N. Security Council in late May 1992 
against Yugoslavia over its alleged involvement in the civil war 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina threatened the living standard of some 
10.8 million people with galloping hyperinflation which 
literally devalued any wages by the hour and on the other hand 
invited spiralling price hikes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

