<F P=100> SLOVENIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Controversy Over Krsko Nuclear Plant Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Croatia To Ignore Krsko Ban </H4>
<F P=102> AU1201162494 Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network in Slovene 
1430 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1201162494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ljubljana Radio Slovenia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovene </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Irena Majce] </F>
  [Text] Last night's optimistic and somewhat mysterious 
statement by Croatian Economic Minister Nadan Vidosevic, at 
Otocec, that problems regarding the nuclear power plant will be 
solved in a few days and that Croatia would get electricity in 
conformity with the technical possibilities of the power plant, 
was finally cleared up by today's statement by the main Croatian 
duty official at Krsko, Jakov Sinovcic. Sinovcic said, among 
other things, the following: 
  [Begin Sinovcic recording in Serbo-Croatian] Whatever is 
produced at any moment, the Croatian electricity board is going 
to take 50 percent of. [end recording] 
  Therefore, Croatia plans to help itself from the system, 
irrespective of the Slovene Government bans. This is 
technically possible, but since our duty officers can register 
such unauthorized use, it is obvious that this will be in 
violation of the agreed exchange. 

</TEXT>

