<H3> <TI>   Havel Briefs Cabinet on Clinton Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1301161794 Prague CTK in English 1419 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1301161794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 13 (CTK) -- Czech President Vaclav 
Havel and Premier Vaclav Klaus, at a cabinet meeting today, gave 
a broad report on U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit in Prague, 
during which Clinton held talks with Visegrad Group leaders (the 
Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Poland), among other things, 
about their countries' attitude toward the North Atlantic 
Alliance. 
  "The cabinet listened to the reports with satisfaction and 
expressed... gratitude," Klaus told journalists, adding that the 
issue had been also discussed at the session in a matter-of-fact 
manner. 
  Asked about a meeting of the presidents of the Czech 
Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Germany, Poland, and Austria 
reported yesterday to be planned for on April 14-15 in the east 
Bohemian city of Litomysl, Havel said "such a meeting was under 
preparation and would be held as an unofficial one on the 
occasion of some cultural event." However, Havel said that for 
the time being nobody was capable of saying anything specific 
about the planned meeting. 
  The meeting was preliminarily planned during a similar 
meeting in July in Salzburg, where Czech, German, Austrian, and 
Hungarian Presidents Vaclav Havel, Thomas Klestil, Richard von 
Weizsaecker, and Arpad Goncz met on the occasion of the Salzburg 
musical festival. 

</TEXT>

