<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Repatriation of Ukrainian Czechs Terminated </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1401081894 Prague CTK in English 1842 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1401081894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Jan 12 (CTK) -- The Economics Ministry has 
dissolved the working group in charge of organizing the 
repatriation of ethnic Czechs from the Ukrainian region of 
Volhynia who were hit by radioactivity following the 1986 
accident at a reactor of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant. The 
operation will not continue any longer, Ruzena Misonova, a 
member of the working group, told CTK today. 
  Misonova said that the operation, which had been first 
initiated by the Czechoslovak Government and later continued by 
the Czech one, enabled 1,812 Volhynian Czechs to move to the 
Czech Republic, of whom 889 were repatriated in 1991, 505 in 
1992, and 418 in 1993. 
  Three hundred applications for repatriation remain to be 
settled. As no law exists on conditions of repatriation of 
ethnic Czechs living abroad, these and other possible applicants 
will be treated in the same way as any foreigners who ask for 
permission to stay permanently in the Czech Republic and for 
Czech citizenship, Misonova explained. 
  The Association of Volhynian Czechs and Their Friends 
insists 
that at least one official from the Interior Ministry should be 
charged to settle the problems of Czechs from Volhynia. Vaclav 
Landa, the association's representative in charge of the 
repatriation, told CTK that the association was likely to ask 
the Economics Ministry to solve the present situation. 
  Volhynia is a historical region situated in Ukraine where 
many Czechs moved in the course of the 19th century, creating a 
significant, economically, and culturally active ethnic 
minority. Their total before World War Two was about 40,000. 
  In 1946-47, a large number of Volhynian Czechs were 
repatriated under an inter-governmental agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-49697 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu010__a94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-010-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 January 1994 </DATE1>

