<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Officials Preparing for `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1301151194 Budapest MTI in English 1400 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1301151194 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 13 January (MTI) -- Defense officials 
have been working on plans for joining NATO's peace-partnership 
process since October, Hungarian Defense Policymaker Csaba Kiss 
said on Thursday [13 January]. Defense planning and spending 
need to be more open and in line with NATO standards, and under 
stronger civilian control. Defense Ministry and Army Command 
links, cut in 1989, need to be repaired. 
  In future, Hungarian soldiers will participate in 
peace-keeping operations not just as observers, and there will 
be independent subunits for humanitarian assistance and tackling 
disasters. Various subunits will be picked to cooperate with 
NATO troops. Small-scale joint exercises are expected in the 
second half of this year. 
  Hungary's air defense and airspace observation should also 
be 
converted to NATO formats, airplanes being fitted with 
friend-or-foe identification systems and ground radars 
overhauled so as to be able to communicate with NATO planes. 
  Two Hungarian military planners will soon go to NATO's 
Brussels headquarters. Kiss hopes the Ministry can cover extra 
costs from involvement in the new NATO program out of budget 
reserves. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

