<H3> <TI>   Olechowski: Poland `More Secure,' Closer to NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301233594 Warsaw PAP in English 1710 GMT 13 Jan 93 </F>
<F P=103> LD1301233594 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Jan. 13 -- Polish Foreign Minister Andrzej 
Olechowski told a press conference Thursday that "Poland is more 
secure today than yesterday" and a "step closer to NATO." He 
expressed such an opinion after the Visegrad Group summit 
attended by President Bill Clinton on Wednesday. 
  Olechowski said that the "Partnership for Peace" had a 
significant influence on European security and stressed that 
only democratic countries could take part in this process. 
  The "Partnership for Peace" initiative consolidates the 
possibilities of preserving and restoring peace at the time of 
crisis and also gives Poland an access to NATO technologies and 
information, as well as to Western early warning systems. 
  The foreign minister also recalled that Poland signed 
treaties with all the neighbouring countries apart from 
Lithuania but he stressed that negotiations on the 
Polish-Lithuanian treaty were under way and are expected to be 
concluded at the end of January. 

</TEXT>

