<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar on Capacities of Arms Industry for NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1301174194 Prague CTK in English 1644 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1301174194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Jan 13 (CTK) -- Within the Partnership 
for Peace, Slovakia has offered NATO the capacities of its arms 
industry and cooperation in developing military equipment, 
Slovak Premier Vladimir Meciar told journalists today. 
  Speaking at a press conference after top Visegrad Four (the 
Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland, and Slovakia) representatives 
met with U.S. President Bill Clinton on Wednesday in Prague, 
Meciar said that Slovak arms production could not compete with 
that of NATO's, given, among other things, the existence of two 
military systems in the past. 
  Slovak heavy weaponry is of good mechanical quality, while 
its electronic systems are improving, Meciar stated. 
  Slovakia's arms production dropped in 1993 to 8 to 9 percent 
of its 1989 level. This is a huge decline, which cannot be 
called conversion to peaceful purposes. The conversion should 
represent a change of 5 percent a year, Meciar stressed. 
  The present situation in the Slovak arms industry is due to 
bad decisions by the former Czechoslovak Federal Government, 
which halted the final production of arms without regard to 
continuing supplies, which mostly came from the Czech Republic. 
This resulted in billion losses, Meciar said. He stressed that 
the Czech Republic was now striving to revive the production of 
military systems, which had been halted in Slovakia. 
  A joint-stock company with state participation, aimed at 
exporting Slovak arms, has been founded in Slovakia. A 
commission has also been set up to decide on each deal, Meciar 
concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

