<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croats, Serbs Extend Cease-Fire Until 30 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1301193694 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1800 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1301193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Talks were held in the Karlovac suburb of Turanj 
today. The Croatian side was represented by General Petar 
Stipetic, commander of the Zagreb operational zone, Pavle 
Miljevac, commander of the Karlovac operational zone, Captain 
Davor Domazet, and Slavko Degoricija, chairman of the state 
commission for talks with rebel Serbs. The Serbian side was 
headed by Colonel Kosta Novakovic, while General (Met Guiness) 
attended the talks on behalf of the UN Protection Forces 
[UNPROFOR]. A statement was issued after three hours of talks 
saying that the [Christmas] cease-fire [between Serbs and Croats 
in Croatia] was honored and that it has been extended until 31 
January. The talks will be resumed at state commission level. 
It was concluded that expert military groups should be formed 
to prepare an agreement on a lasting truce. 

</TEXT>

