<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akashi `Encouraged' By Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1301150794 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1301150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] We have just received a report that Federal Prime 
Minister Radoje Kontic received Yasushi Akashi, special envoy of 
the UN Secretary General for the former Yugoslavia and a new 
head of UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] for Yugoslavia. After 
the talks, which were held behind closed doors, Akashi briefly 
addressed journalists, telling them that he and Kontic discussed 
the declaration issued at the NATO summit, which asks UNPROFOR 
to study the possibilities of protecting Srebrenica and Tuzla 
airport. Akashi announced that he will go to Geneva to meet 
Secretary General Butrus-Ghali and hold consultations on these 
issues. He explained that he and Thorvald Stoltenberg will have 
different obligations and that he will stay on the territory of 
the former Yugoslavia. 
  I will help the negotiators in Geneva as much as I can. They 
will rely on the information that I will send them from the 
field. I think that this will help, and hope that it will bring 
about positive results sooner, Akashi said. Prime Minister 
Kontic and I discussed bilateral relations between the Yugoslav 
Government and UNPROFOR, and must say that I am quite encouraged 
by his views, Akashi told journalists. 

</TEXT>

